 Lists Event Directory Glossary Greeting Cards Halachic Times Jewish Calendar Judaica Store Knowledge Base SMS Shabbat Times Yahrtzeit Lookup Popular Tools: Jewish Calendar Shabbat Times Ask the Rabbi Chabad Locator Email Subscriptions Judaica Store Donate English עברית Español Français Deutsch Português Русский Italiano More Sites Today is Sat. Jun. 27, 2026 | Tammuz 12, 5786 This week's Torah reading is Chukat-Balak Jewish Holidays Comprehensive sites for each of the Jewish holidays\" data-ctooltip-location=\"bottom\">Jewish Holidays TheRebbe.org A site dedicated to the teachings and life of the Lubavitcher Rebbe\" data-ctooltip-location=\"bottom\">TheRebbe.org Chabad.org Video 20,000 videos in hundreds of genres, topics and styles\" data-ctooltip-location=\"bottom\">Chabad.org Video ChabadU Advance your Jewish knowledge with online courses\" data-ctooltip-location=\"bottom\">ChabadU Chabad.org Audio Downloadable audio classes, music and more\" data-ctooltip-location=\"bottom\">Audio Classes Chabad.org News News about Chabad-Lubavitch and the Jewish world\" data-ctooltip-location=\"bottom\">News Kosher Cooking Thousands of kosher recipes at your fingertips\" data-ctooltip-location=\"bottom\"> Torah Texts Explore a world of Jewish knowledge and texts for all levels and backgrounds\" data-ctooltip-location=\"bottom\">Torah Texts TheJewishWoman.org The site for Jewish women\" data-ctooltip-location=\"bottom\">The Jewish Woman JewishKids.org A site for Jewish children\" data-ctooltip-location=\"bottom\">Jewish Kids Jewish Practice Learning & Values Community & Family Inspiration & Entertainment ב\"ה Learning & Values The Seven Laws of Noah The 7 Noahide Laws Chabad.org Staff What Are the Seven Noahide Laws? The 7 Noahide Laws are rules that all of us must keep, regardless of who we are or from where we come. Without these seven things, it would be impossible for humanity to live together in harmony. Do not profane G‑d ’s Oneness in any way. Acknowledge that there is a single G‑d who cares about what we are doing and desires that we take care of His world. Do not curse your Creator. No matter how angry you may be, do not take it out verbally against your Creator. Do not murder . The value of human life cannot be measured. To destroy a single human life is to destroy the entire world—because, for that person, the world has ceased to exist. It follows that by sustaining a single human life, you are sustaining an entire universe. Do not eat a limb of a still-living animal. Respect the life of all G‑d’s creatures. As intelligent beings, we have a duty not to cause undue pain to other creatures. Do not steal . Whatever benefits you receive in this world, make sure that none of them are at the unfair expense of someone else. Harness and channel the human libido. Incest, adultery, and homosexual relations are forbidden. The family unit is the foundation of human society. Sexuality is the fountain of life and so nothing is more holy than the sexual act. So, too, when abused, nothing can be more debasing and destructive to the human being. Establish courts of law and ensure justice in our world. With every small act of justice, we are restoring harmony to our world, synchronizing it with a supernal order. That is why we must keep the laws established by our government for the country’s stability and harmony. In this article: Why Are the Noahide Laws Especially Important Today? Why Are They Called the Noahide Laws? More Noahide Laws Who Keeps the Noahide Laws? Why Are the Noahide Laws Especially Important Today? These laws were communicated by G‑d to Adam and Noah , ancestors of all human beings. That is what makes these rules universal, for all times, places and people: Laws made by humans may change according to circumstance. But laws made by the Creator of all souls over all of time remain the same for all people at all times.. If we would fulfill these laws just because they make sense to us, then we would change them, according to our convenience. We would be our own god. But when we understand that they are the laws of a supreme G‑d, we understand that they can not be changed, just as He does not change. Today, we are on the verge of a new era for humankind, a time when we will finally live together in peace and the world will be filled with divine wisdom. Those who keep these basic rules will have a share in that world, since, after all, they took part in making it possible. Although these teachings were recorded in the sacred Jewish texts, for many centuries Jews were not able to speak about them to the people they lived amongst. But in recent times, the foremost rabbi of the Jewish people in the 20th century, Rabbi Menachem M. Schneerson , of righteous memory, encouraged Jews to publicize these teachings, so that the world can prepare for the times of peace and wisdom that are swiftly approaching. Why Are They Called the Noahide Laws? These are called the Noahide Laws because they are the heritage of humanity from our oldest ancestors. Since all humanity are descendants of Noah , who survived the Great Flood , all people today are Noahides . Jewish tradition tells that six of these laws were given to the first human being, Adam . A seventh law, the prohibition against eating the limb of a living animal, was given to Noah when humankind was permitted to consume meat. More Noahide Laws These seven principles are general ones. Many other teachings, all intuitive to the upright human mind, branch out from these. These include the practice of charity and acts of kindness , honoring and respecting parents , prayer to G‑d and contemplation of His wisdom and greatness. This also means not acting recklessly towards the magnificent creation that has been entrusted to our stewardship. Who Keeps the Noahide Laws? Nobody needs to convert or join a particular church or temple to keep these principles and laws. But it is important to keep them because this is what the supreme G‑d wants of every one of us, and not only because they are wise and good laws. Anyone who keeps these basic rules for that reason—regardless of race, nationality or culture—is considered a righteous person and granted eternal life upon leaving this world. Click here to learn more about the Noahide Covenant. Seven Noahide Laws Chabad.org Magazine Subscribe to Chabad.org Magazine Subscribe Thank you for subscribing! A confirmation will be sent to . More subscription options &copy; Copyright, all rights reserved. If you enjoyed this article, we encourage you to distribute it further, provided that you comply with Chabad.org's copyright policy . You may also be interested in... The Seven Step Plan for World Peace An overview of the Seven Noahide Laws Watch (1:30:02) 2 Comments Seven Laws for a Beautiful Planet The Noahide Tradition 69 Comments What Are the Seven Noahide Laws? Watch (4:39) 42 Comments The Discovery of Planet Earth On the seven universal laws of life 63 Comments Join the Discussion 516 Comments Newest Oldest Posting Guidelines characters remaining Name Location Email * will not be published Email me when new comments are posted. Please send me Chabad.org's weekly Magazine and periodic emails. We will not share your email address. Cancel Submit Trudi Adeoshun. Ibadan June 9, 2026 I am an initiate of an African religion. I have my own moral compass and I don&#39;t think anyone should impose theirs on mine. Reply Robert USA June 9, 2026 in response to Trudi Adeoshun. : Why then dabble in organized religion? Reply Rivkah New Jersey June 9, 2026 in response to Trudi Adeoshun. : If people live according to their own moral compass they can make horrific mistakes. The Nazis thought it was moral to eliminate Jews, and others from the face of the earth. Obviously that was not moral. Only when we follow G-d&#39;s commandments can we be sure we&#39;re living an ethical life. G-d created the concept of right and wrong. G-d &quot;imposes,&quot; gives life to all whether they want it or not. He will also &quot;impose,&quot; give death to the person when He sees fit. Can anyone tell G-d what He should impose on them or not? He is the Boss of all, Master of the Universe, Who creates and maintains everyone and everything as long as He wishes to. The commandments G-d gave us are gifts and opportunities to help us, if we do them, and to give us magnificent blessings. The sooner we can learn to be humble and &quot;make G-d&#39;s will our will,&quot; the sooner we can receive these blessings and avoid the opposite of blessings. Reply Pamela Weinstein Port Saint Lucie June 11, 2026 in response to Trudi Adeoshun. : Idk why you even bothered to post here, then. You have nothing to gain, if you aren&#39;t interested in learning about anything other than your own way of living . No one needed to know that your way is the only way Reply Rafael Alaska May 18, 2026 I dont know if I asked this before but why be fruitfull and multiply is not in the list? Reply Eliezer Zalmanov for Chabad.org May 19, 2026 in response to Rafael: The simple answer is that according to the Talmud, non-Jews are not commanded to procreate (Sanhedrin 59b). The Talmud explains that not every command given in the Torah applies universally. As a general rule, laws that were given only before Mount Sinai became part of the Jewish covenant, while laws that were repeated after Sinai can apply more broadly to all humanity. Procreation is understood as one of the commandments that remains specifically a Jewish obligation. That said, Judaism does not teach that non-Jews only have seven responsibilities. The Seven Noahide Laws are more like a core framework of universal moral obligations, mostly focused on what a person should not do. The Talmud discusses additional responsibilities and values for all people beyond those seven. So, the best way to explain this is that having children is not viewed as a religious obligation in the same way it is for Jews, but there is still value in it for all of humanity. Reply Rafael May 19, 2026 in response to Eliezer Zalm",
